{{Infobox deity
|TITLE = Kenmet
|NAME = <hiero>V31:N35-X1 G14-N14</hiero>
|NAME-ERWEITERT = {{ill|Middle Kingdom (Egypt)|de|Mittleres Reich|ja|中王国|12=draft|12=draft}}
|NAME2 = <hiero>V31:N35-T34-G17-N14-X1:H8-C10</hiero><br/>Kenmet<br/>''Knmt''<br/>''[Translation not possible]''
|NAME2-ERWEITERT = {{ill|Egypt in Greco-Roman Period|de|Gr.-röm. Zeit|ja|ギリシャ・ローマ時代|12=draft|12=draft}}
}}

'''Kenmet''' (also '''Kenmut, Chnoubis, Chnoumis, Chnouphis, Knuphis''') is attested as an {{ill|Ancient Egypt|de|Altes Ägypten|ja|古代エジプト|12=draft|12=draft}}ian {{ill|Serpent Deity|de|Schlangengottheit|ja|蛇神|12=draft|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Celestial Sphere|de|Himmelskugel|ja|天球|12=draft|12=draft}}, first in the {{ill|Coffin Texts|de|Sargtexte|ja|棺文|12=draft|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Middle Kingdom (Egypt)|de|Mittleres Reich|ja|中王国|lt=of the Middle Kingdom|lt_de=Mittleren Reiches|lt_ja=中王国の|12=draft|12=draft}} as well as in the associated {{ill|Diagonal Star Clock|de|Diagonalsternuhr|ja|対角星時計|12=draft|12=draft}}.

At the same time, Kenmet appears in the {{ill|Book of Nut|de|Nutbuch|ja|ヌトの書|12=draft|12=draft}} as the eponymous {{ill|Decan Kenmet|de|Kenmet (Dekan)|ja|ケンメト（デカン）|12=draft|12=draft}} in the role of the constellation responsible for the {{ill|Flooding of the Nile|de|Nilschwemme|ja|ナイルの氾濫|12=draft|12=draft}}.

The association frequently made in the {{ill|Secondary Literature|de|Sekundärliteratur|ja|二次文献|12=draft|12=draft}} between the names ''Chnoubis, Chnoumis'' (and similar) and the deity {{ill|Chnum|de|Chnum|ja|クム|12=draft|12=draft}} is untenable, since, for example, the so‐called ''Chnouphis sign'' found on {{ill|Gemmae|de|Gemme|ja|宝石|12=draft|12=draft}} can be attributed to {{ill|Decan Kenmet|de|Kenmet (Dekan)|ja|ケンメト（デカン）|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>Alexandra von Lieven: ''Der Himmel über Esna''. p. 59.</ref>

== Background ==
=== Representations and Functions ===
[[File:Ägyptischer Maler um 1360 v. Chr. 001.jpg|thumb|Depiction of Isis in the New Kingdom]]
In the Middle Kingdom, Kenmet is iconographically represented both as an erect snake, crossed by three smaller snakes, and as a snake with a falcon or human head. At the same time, Kenmet embodies the attributes of a {{ill|Ram|de|Widders|ja|牡羊|12=draft|12=draft}} (''Ba''), of {{ill|Re (Egyptian mythology)|de|Re (ägyptische Mythologie)|ja|レ|12=draft|12=draft}}, and of {{ill|Isis|de|Isis|ja|イシス|12=draft|12=draft}}.

During the {{ill|Third Intermediate Period (Egypt)|de|Dritte Zwischenzeit (Ägypten)|ja|第三中間期|12=draft|12=draft}}, Kenmet venerates the activities of {{ill|Amun-Re|de|Amun-Re|ja|アメン・レ|12=draft|12=draft}} in connection with his manifestation as {{ill|Ra-Horakhty|de|Re-Harachte|ja|レ＝ハラハテ|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Horakhty|de|Harachte|ja|ハラハテ|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Chepri|de|Chepre|ja|チェプレ|lt=Chepri|lt_de=Chepri|lt_ja=チェプレ|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Atum|de|Atum|ja|アトゥム|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Harmachis|de|Harmachis|ja|ハルマキス|12=draft|12=draft}}.

In the {{ill|Egypt in the Greco-Roman Period|de|Ägypten in griechisch-römischer Zeit|ja|ギリシャ・ローマ時代のエジプト|12=draft|12=draft}}, Kenmet's function as Isis is equated with the character traits of {{ill|Sopdet|de|Sopdet|ja|ソプデト|12=draft|12=draft}} as the bearer of the {{ill|Eye of Re|de|Auge des Re|ja|レの目|12=draft|12=draft}}.

=== Mythological Aspects ===
In the {{ill|New Kingdom|de|Neues Reich|ja|新王国|12=draft|12=draft}}, Kenmet, together with the two celestial turtles, represents the ''Life of {{ill|Horus|de|Horus|ja|ホルス|12=draft|12=draft}}''. Kenmet is the deity who departs on {{ill|Achet|de|Achet|ja|アヘト|lt=15. Achet IV|lt_de=15. Achet IV|lt_ja=15.アヘトIV|12=draft|12=draft}} to bring "the time of {{ill|Osiris|de|Osiris|ja|オシリス|12=draft|12=draft}}" ({{ill|Season|de|Jahreszeit|ja|季節|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|October|de|Oktober|ja|10月|12=draft|12=draft}}).

In the Greco-Roman period, Kenmet, as the Horus of {{ill|Letopolis|de|Letopolis|ja|レトポリス|12=draft|12=draft}} (''Hem'', northwest of {{ill|Memphis (Egypt)|de|Memphis (Ägypten)|ja|メンフィス|12=draft|12=draft}}), embodied the season of sowing, which is why Kenmet was also designated as a recipient in the {{ill|Sacrificial Cult|de|Opfer (Religion)|ja|犠牲祭|12=draft|12=draft}}. Additionally, in this epoch, Kenmet was the {{ill|Chronocrat|de|Chronokrat|ja|クロノクラート|12=draft|12=draft}} of the first hour of the night and stood as the "armored one at the head of the divine {{ill|Star|de|Stern|ja|星|12=draft|12=draft}}s during their rotation".

== See also ==
* {{ill|List of Egyptian Deities|de|Liste der ägyptischen Götter|ja|エジプトの神々の一覧|12=draft|12=draft}}

== Literature ==
* {{ill|Christian Leitz|de|Christian Leitz|ja|クリスチャン・ライツ|12=draft|12=draft}} et al.: ''{{ill|Lexicon of Egyptian Deities and Deity Names|de|Lexikon der ägyptischen Götter und Götterbezeichnungen|ja|エジプト神と神名の辞典|12=draft|12=draft}}''. Peeters, Leuven 2002, ISBN 90-429-1146-8, p. 290.
* {{ill|Alexandra von Lieven|de|Alexandra von Lieven|ja|アレクサンドラ・フォン・リーベン|12=draft|12=draft}}: ''Outline of the Course of the Stars – The so‑called Book of Nut''. The Carsten Niebuhr Institute of Ancient Eastern Studies et al., Copenhagen 2007, ISBN 978-87-635-0406-5.
* Alexandra von Lieven: ''The Sky over Esna – A Case Study on Religious Astronomy in Egypt as Exemplified by the Cosmological Ceiling and Architrave Inscriptions in the Temple of Esna''. Harrassowitz, Wiesbaden 2000, ISBN 3-447-04324-5.
* {{ill|Joachim Friedrich Quack|de|Joachim Friedrich Quack|ja|ヨアヒム・フリードリヒ・クアック|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kim Ryholt|de|Kim Ryholt|ja|キム・リヨルト|12=draft|12=draft}}: ''Hieratic texts from the collection - The Carlsberg papyri 7 -''. Museum Tusculanum Press, Copenhagen 2006, ISBN 87-635-0405-7.

